@kisstkondoros thanks for the PR!  - It makes sense to add a feature to convert indentation only in the selection - however the issue with your approach is that it can be cryptic to the user that only the selection gets changed. What would happen if a use accidently has something selected and triggers that action - there is no UI indication that only the selection is being replaced. We could change the title of the action - but then the title would be too long and ugly imho. Suggestions on how to solve this are welcome - Changing not only the beggining but every occurence - is this something standard that all other text editors support? Because if we change this then the name of the acitons need to be also changed - as that is not indentation. Indentation is by definitaiton only the start of a line.  Due to the reasons above I am rejecting this PR. Though I could be convinced otherwise. So feedback is very welcome @kisstkondoros @alexandrudima

@roblourens your proposal for allowing to run a debug session for a non-existing debug type is problematic because you are missing out all the other contributions of the extension. In addition it would be an effort (hack) for us to implement that.  Please consider these (existing) solutions: 1. Open the debug extension in VS Code and then run the extension with F5 (or Control-F5). This will launch another VS Code windows that 'knows' the debug type (and has all the associated contributions for that type) and you can then start your debug session against a debug server safely from there. Since you do **not** have to restart the debug extension when restarting the debug server, it is not a big pain. I'm using this approach all the time now. 2. If you don't like the additional step to launch the debug extension once, you can side install your debug extension in your ~/.vscode/extensions folder. This does not have to be the final extension. Just a folder with a package.json that contributes the new type is enough.  /cc @isidorn

Current state: - Code is ready for merging into master (see https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/issues/7656). - We miss the editor title area contribution. This is being addressed in #3192. - The display performance is sub-par. See updates in #7066. - Toggling between source and preview using the same keyboard shortcut is limited by #6941. Current workaround is to use the `workbench.action.navigateBack` command.

The term preview is used to describe this behaviour in Visual Studio and in Sublime Text so it's not an uncommon term (Atom calls them Pending tabs). We could always rethink the way we use it for markdown files. However, if we go with pinned and unpinned tabs we could have settings like so:  "workbench.editor.unpinnedTabs.enableInExplorer": true, "workbench.editor.unpinnedTabs.enableInQuickOpen": true and anywhere else we want to enable unpinned tabs.  We should be aware though that we might have a need in the future to also support what Visual Studio calls pinned tabs - pinned tabs are positioned to the left hand side and newly opened tabs appear to the right of all pinned tabs.

Node debug adapter is an extension which gets packed in vscode as part of our build process. So when you run vscode out of source it is missing. In order to overcome that you need to copy the node debug extension from an installed vscode (search for node-debug inside your vscode install location) to the extension folder of vscode-oss-dev\extensions (this should live in your users folder I think). We would like to optimise the design such that the file names remain glanceable for most of the time. We think that showing the file name is more important for developers than showing the name of the web page is when browsing the web.

@weinand Indeed. But I suspect that Code doesn't executes the 'foo.cmd' on Windows but tries to execute 'foo' which is for `Unix` like OS. You have to tell it explicitly the `runtimeExecutable` file extension.  If I were you (and I'm not) I would have added a file extension check for Windows and add the `.cmd` if the user hasn't specified it. It's an internal handling (which you may not prefer) but improves the user experience with Code and Electron.  Though having the OS properties now kinda solves this issue.  Still the issue with using `--enable-logging` remains.

I don't think that the scope is sufficient but that the completion item will know. Think of such JS code and the cursor being inside the curly brackets. In that case it makes sense to complete on dot.  ``` js  /**  * @param {foo.ba|} a  */  function foo(a) {  } ```  A sample the other way around would be writing a number literal for which someone proposes completions. I then might not make sense to complete on dot  ``` js var n = 33.| ```  Therefore I think either the provider or the item should define if it can be completed on a completion character.
